          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>Bifolium, Parchment, Shelfmark: HC.MS.03171, Writing surface: parchment; Qurʾānic Text: 23:39-43; 23:43-44; 23:66-69; 23:69-23:71; Lines per page: 5; Dimensions: bifolium (open): 184-127 x 313-252 mm; with integrations: 196 x 323 (vertical format); Script style Ductus: New Style (type I); </p>
              <p>Estimated date of production: 950-1050. The use of NS.I script is generally associated with a production date of  the 10th or 11th century, although its use continued until the early  13th century (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">Déroche 1992, pp. 132-5</ref>). However, the fact that the  writing surface is parchment rather than paper may indicate a 10th or  early 11th century origin, since the use of parchment was obsolete by  the mid-11th century everywhere except in the Maghrib and  Andalusia.</p>
              <p>Illumination: Single verse divisions are marked with a small gold rosettes. Tenth verse divisions are marked within the text with a small gold roundel with a central green dot (now oxidised to brown), plus a larger illuminated gold and brown roundel containing an eight-pointed star and the exact verse count written in gold kūfī script in the margin opposite.</p>
              <p>Recent provenance of this bifolium: Sotheby’s, London, 21 November 1985, lot 294.</p>
              <p>Sister leaves: The present bifolium comes from a fragment of six folios (probably three bifolia) whose full text is not known but includes 023:039-023:044; 023:048-023:052, 023:066-023:069, 023:069-023:071 (Sotheby’s, London, 21 November 1985, lot 294). No further sister leaves are currently known.</p>
              <p/>
            </summary>
