          <physDesc>
            <objectDesc>
              <supportDesc material="parchment">
                <support>
                  <p>The sequence of text on this bifolium is as follows: Page 1 (fol 1a): 23:39-43 (hair side), Page 2 (fol 1b): 23:43-44 (flesh side), Page 3 (fol 2a):  23:66-69 (flesh side), Page 4 (fol 2b): 23:69-71 (hair side).</p>
                  <p>The  sequence of text on each page of this bifolium indicates that it was  one of the outer bifolia in a quire (gathering) of bifolia. There is a  break of 22 verses of text between the last word on page 2 (fol 1b,  018:044) and the first word on page 3 (fol 2a, 018:066). Each page  carries an average of 2.5 verses, so there were probably eight pages of  text between the two, or two further bifolia, meaning that the quire  consisted of at least 3 bifolia (12 pages). While we cannot know exactly  what the quire structure would have been, since there may have been a  further bifolium or bifolia outside the present bifolium, it is  interesting to note that ternions (gatherings of three bifolia) were  used in Qur’ans in New Style scripts as well as the established practice  of quinions (gatherings of five bifolia) and quaternions (four  bifolia), see <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">François Déroche, The Abbasid Tradition, London, 1992, p. 134</ref>.  The sequence of text on the present pages and observation of the  parchment surface itself indicate that the hair side was the outer side  of the bifolium and the flesh side on the inner side.</p>
